\section{W$^*$-bundles, Fibres and Restrictions}
This section contains the basic properties of tracially continuous W$^*$-bundles that we shall need in the sequel. We begin by recalling the definition of a tracially continuous W$^*$-bundle from \cite[Section 5]{Oz13}.
\begin{dfn} \label{dfn:WBundle}
A tracially continuous W$^*$-bundle consists of the following data:
\begin{itemize}
	\item a compact Hausdorff space $X$;
	\item a unital C$^*$-algebra ${\mathcal{M}}$;
	\item a unital embedding $C(X) \subseteq Z({\mathcal{M}})$;
	\item a conditional expectation $E:{\mathcal{M}} \rightarrow C(X)$.
\end{itemize}
Moreover, the following axioms must be satisfied:
\begin{itemize}
	\item[(T)] $E(a_1a_2) = E(a_2a_1)$, for all $a_1,a_2 \in {\mathcal{M}}$;
	\item[(F)] $E(a^*a) = 0 \Rightarrow a = 0$, for all $a \in {\mathcal{M}}$; 
	\item[(C)] the unit ball $\lbrace a \in {\mathcal{M}}: \|a\| \leq 1 \rbrace$ is complete with respect to the norm defined by $\|a\|_{2,u} = \|E(a^*a)^{1/2}\|_{C(X)}$.
\end{itemize}
\end{dfn}

We shall abbreviate \emph{tracially continuous W$^*$-bundle} to \emph{W$^*$-bundle} or even \emph{bundle} when there is no chance of confusion. We shall call $X$ the base space of the bundle, ${\mathcal{M}}$ the section algebra of the bundle, and $E$ the conditional exception. We shall speak of the tracial axiom, the faithfulness axiom and the completeness axiom respectively. We shall often confuse the bundle itself with its section algebra, and speak of the bundle ${\mathcal{M}}$. We shall often fix the base space $X$ and speak of bundles over $X$.

It is instructive to consider the case where $X$ is the one point space $\lbrace * \rbrace$. We identify $\mathbb{C}$, $C(\lbrace * \rbrace)$, and $\mathbb{C}1_{{\mathcal{M}}}$. Now the data for a W$^*$-bundle over $X$ reduces to a unital C$^*$-algebra ${\mathcal{M}}$ and a state. The first two axioms then require this state to be a faithful trace. The effect of the third axiom is to ensure that the image of the unit ball of ${\mathcal{M}}$ under the GNS representation corresponding to this faithful trace is ultraweakly closed (see for example \cite[Lemma A.3.3]{Si08}). A W$^*$-bundle over a one point space is, therefore, just a tracial von Neumann algebra.

